Great — this is one of the most important LLD patterns for interviews. I’ll simplify and structure everything so you can explain + implement confidently.

🧠 1️⃣ Command Pattern — One Line
Encapsulate a request as an object so you can parameterize, queue, log, and undo operations.
🎯 Why We Need It (Your AC Example)
❌ Problem Without Command
ac.turnOn();
ac.setTemp(24);
ac.turnOff();
Issues:
🚫 1. Tight Coupling
Client knows EVERYTHING about AC

What methods to call

In what sequence

How logic works

🚫 2. No Undo/Redo
No history of actions

Can't revert easily

Client must track everything ❌

🚫 3. Poor Scalability
Add new device → client changes

AC + Bulb + Fan → client becomes HUGE

💡 Core Idea of Command Pattern
Break into 3 parts:
Invoker → Command → Receiver
Visual Flow
4
🧩 Components (VERY IMPORTANT)
1️⃣ Receiver (Actual Logic)
class AirConditioner {
    void turnOn() { ... }
    void turnOff() { ... }
}

👉 Does real work
👉 “Dumb object”

2️⃣ Command Interface
interface Command {
    void execute();
    void undo();   // optional but powerful
}
3️⃣ Concrete Commands
class TurnOnACCommand implements Command {
    AirConditioner ac;

    public void execute() {
        ac.turnOn();
    }

    public void undo() {
        ac.turnOff();
    }
}
4️⃣ Invoker (Remote Control)
class RemoteControl {
    Command command;

    void pressButton() {
        command.execute();
    }
}
5️⃣ Client
remote.setCommand(new TurnOnACCommand(ac));
remote.pressButton();
🧠 What Changed?
Before
Client → AC directly ❌
After
Client → Remote → Command → AC ✅
🔥 BIG BENEFITS
✅ 1. Loose Coupling
Client doesn’t know AC internals anymore
✅ 2. Easy Undo/Redo
Store commands → reverse them
✅ 3. Extensible
Add new command → no change in client
✅ 4. Supports Logging / Queue
Commands can be stored, delayed, replayed
🔁 Undo / Redo (VERY IMPORTANT)
Idea:

👉 Maintain a stack of commands

Implementation
Stack<Command> history = new Stack<>();
On Execute
command.execute();
history.push(command);
On Undo
Command last = history.pop();
last.undo();
Flow
Press → execute → store  
Undo → pop → reverse
🔥 Example Flow
1. Press ON → AC ON → push
2. Press OFF → AC OFF → push
3. Undo → pop OFF → AC ON
4. Undo → pop ON → AC OFF
🎯 Real-Life Examples
📺 Remote Control
Button = Command
TV/AC = Receiver
✂️ Text Editor
Copy, Paste, Undo
💳 Banking
Transfer money (can rollback)
🧾 Order System
Place order → cancel order
⚠️ Interview Trick Questions
❓ Where is undo stored?

👉 In Invoker (Remote)

❓ Who knows undo logic?

👉 Command class

❓ Can we support redo?

👉 Yes → use two stacks

Undo stack  
Redo stack
🔄 Command vs Other Patterns
Command vs Strategy
Command → encapsulates action + receiver  
Strategy → interchangeable algorithms
Command vs Observer
Command → execute action  
Observer → notify changes
Command vs Proxy
Command → represents action  
Proxy → controls access
🧠 When to Use (IMPORTANT)

Use Command when:

✔ Need undo/redo
✔ Need to queue operations
✔ Need to log actions
✔ Need decoupling between sender & receiver
🧠 Memory Trick
“Button doesn’t know what it does”

👉 Button → Command → Receiver

🚀 Interview Perfect Answer
Definition
Command pattern encapsulates a request as an object, allowing parameterization, queuing, logging, and undo/redo operations.
Example
Remote control → button → command → AC
🔥 Final Mental Model
Action = Object